    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1943-11-20T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1943-11-20T00:00:00-05:00" n="239"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d239">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">
                    <persName corresp="#p_RFD1">Roosevelt</persName> Papers: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">President</gloss>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d239fn1">Sent by the White House Map Room to <persName
                            corresp="#p_GDW1">Greer</persName> at Oran, apparently via military
                        channels.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1943-11-20">November 20,
                            1943</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>For the President from Secretary <persName corresp="#p_HC1">Hull</persName>
                </p>
                <p>Ankara reports on November 18 that <persName corresp="#p_MN1">Numan</persName>
                    obtained approval of Party Leaders to reply to <persName corresp="#p_EA1"
                        >Eden</persName> that Turks have now decided in principle to enter the war.
                        <persName corresp="#p_MN1">Numan</persName> agreed that military assistance
                    to Turkey is now the prime consideration and political question of Russian <pb
                        facs="0354" n="262" xml:id="pg_262"/> assurances should be postponed.
                    British believe Turkish decision cannot long remain secret and are concerned
                    about possible premature Axis attack. British evacuated about 1,000 troops from
                    Leros to Turkey, but reported to have lost seven destroyers.</p>
                <p>Ankara reports on November 17 that <persName corresp="#p_PFv1">Von
                        Papen</persName> told Finnish Minister that Turks will not enter War.
                    Minister believes <persName corresp="#p_PFv1">Von Papen</persName> intends to
                    reassure <persName corresp="#p_HA1">Hitler</persName> and, while concealing
                    truth from <persName corresp="#p_HA1">Hitler</persName>, hasten his downfall as
                        <persName corresp="#p_PFv1">Von Papen</persName> stated peace was not
                    possible unless<note n="2" xml:id="d239fn2">This reads “unless and until” in the
                        file copy in the <persName corresp="#p_HC1">Hull</persName> Papers.</note>
                    <persName corresp="#p_HA1">Hitler</persName> and the Nazis were removed from
                    power.</p>
            </div>
